7 And I turned to the sea of all sense;  
8 I said: “What does this one say? and what answers  
9 that other fire? and who are those who make it?”

25 My duke descended in the boat,  
26 and then he made me enter after him;  
27 and only when I was inside it seemed heavy.

34 And I to him: “If I come, I do not stay;  
35 but you who are you, that you have become so ugly?”  
36 He answered: “See that I am one who weeps.”

37 And I to him: “With weeping and with mourning,  
38 cursed spirit, you remain;  
39 that I know you, you are still wholly raw.”

40 Then he stretched both hands to the wood;  
41 for which the shrewd master pushed him,  
42 saying: “Away this side with the other dogs!”.

43 He then with his arms girded my neck;  
44 He kissed my face and said: “Scornful soul,  
45 blessed she who in you was inflamed!  

46 He was in the world a proud person;  
47 goodness is nothing but his memory adorns:  
48 thus his shadow is here furious.

61 All were shouting: “To Filippo Argenti!”;  
62 and the Florentine spirit bizarre  
63 in himself himself he turned with teeth.

64 Here we left it, that I will not narrate further;  
65 but a grief struck my ears,  
66 for which I, with my eye fixed ahead, am startled.

112 You could not hear that which he gave to them;  
113 but he did not stay there with them, guards,  
114 that each within to test turns to.

124 This their arrogance is not new;  
125 for already they used it to a less secret carry,  
126 which without lock still is found.
